  "prompt": "Whom was Muhammad worshipping before getting revelations?",
  "response": "Before receiving divine revelations, Prophet Muhammad is traditionally understood to have been a devout monotheist who maintained belief in a single, unseen God. In the context of pre-Islamic Arabia, where polytheism was widespread and various deities were worshipped, Muhammad is described in Islamic sources as a \"Hanif.\" The Hanifs were individuals who adhered to the pure monotheistic tradition of Abraham (Ibrahim) and rejected the prevalent idol worship of their society.\n\nMuhammad is believed to have spent time in contemplation and meditation, particularly in the Cave of Hira near Mecca, reflecting on spiritual matters and seeking a deeper understanding of faith. During this period, he is said to have engaged in prayer and expressed his belief in one God (Allah), distinguishing his practices from the polytheistic rituals of his environment.\n\nIt's important to note that Islamic teachings emphasize that Muhammad's devotion to one God was consistent even before the commencement of his prophetic mission. Thus, rather than worshipping a specific deity or idols common in Meccan society, he upheld a monotheistic belief system centered on the worship of Allah.\n\n**References:**\n- [Encyclopaedia Britannica on Muhammad](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Muhammad)\n- [The Quran and Islamic Tradition](https://www.quranicstudies.com/)",
